# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: lipid
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The **ABC transporters**, **ATP synthase (ATP)-binding cassette transporters** are a transport system superfamily that is one of the largest and possibly one of the oldest gene families.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] It is represented in all extant phyla, from prokaryotes to humans.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] ABC transporters belong to translocases.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] ABC transporters often consist of multiple subunits, one or two of which are transmembrane proteins and one or two of which are membrane-associated AAA ATPases.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The ATPase subunits utilize the energy of adenosine triphosphate (ATP) binding and hydrolysis to provide the energy needed for the translocation of substrates across membranes, either for uptake or for export of the substrate.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Most of the uptake systems also have an extracytoplasmic receptor, a solute binding protein.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Some homologous ATPases function in non-transport-related processes such as translation of RNA and DNA repair.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Like the ABC exporters, it is possible that the integral membrane proteins of ABC uptake systems also evolved at least three times independently, based on their high resolution three-dimensional structures.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] ABC uptake porters take up a large variety of nutrients, biosynthetic precursors, trace metals and vitamins, while exporters transport lipids, sterols, drugs, and a large variety of primary and secondary metabolites.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Some of these exporters in humans are involved in tumor resistance, cystic fibrosis and a range of other inherited human diseases.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] High level expression of the genes encoding some of these exporters in both prokaryotic and eukaryotic organisms (including human) result in the development of resistance to multiple drugs such as antibiotics and anti-cancer agents.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Hundreds of ABC transporters have been characterized from both prokaryotes and eukaryotes.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] ABC genes are essential for many processes in the cell, and mutations in human genes cause or contribute to several human genetic diseases.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Forty eight ABC genes have been reported in humans.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] ABC transporters are also involved in multiple drug resistance, and this is how some of them were first identified.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] When the ABC transport proteins are overexpressed in cancer cells, they can export anticancer drugs and render tumors resistant.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] ABC transporters utilize the energy of ATP binding and hydrolysis to transport various substrates across cellular membranes.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] They are divided into three main functional categories.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] In prokaryotes, *importers* mediate the uptake of nutrients into the cell.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The substrates that can be transported include ions, amino acids, peptides, sugars, and other molecules that are mostly hydrophilic.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The membrane-spanning region of the ABC transporter protects hydrophilic substrates from the lipids of the membrane bilayer thus providing a pathway across the cell membrane.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Eukaryotes do not possess any importers.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] *Exporters* or *effluxers*, which are present both in prokaryotes and eukaryotes, function as pumps that extrude toxins and drugs out of the cell.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] In gram-negative bacteria, exporters transport lipids and some polysaccharides from the cytoplasm to the periplasm.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The third subgroup of ABC proteins do not function as transporters, but are rather involved in translation and DNA repair processes.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Bacterial ABC transporters are essential in cell viability, virulence, and pathogenicity.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Iron ABC uptake systems, for example, are important effectors of virulence.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Pathogens use siderophores, such as Enterobactin, to scavenge iron that is in complex with high-affinity iron-binding proteins or erythrocytes.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] These are high-affinity iron-chelating molecules that are secreted by bacteria and reabsorb iron into iron-siderophore complexes.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The chvE-gguAB gene in *Agrobacterium tumefaciens* encodes glucose and galactose importers that are also associated with virulence.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Transporters are extremely vital in cell survival such that they function as protein systems that counteract any undesirable change occurring in the cell.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] For instance, a potential lethal increase in osmotic strength is counterbalanced by activation of osmosensing ABC transporters that mediate uptake of solutes.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Other than functioning in transport, some bacterial ABC proteins are also involved in the regulation of several physiological processes.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] They also play important roles in biosynthetic pathways, including extracellular polysaccharide biosynthesis and cytochrome biogenesis.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Although most eukaryotic ABC transporters are effluxers, some are not directly involved in transporting substrates.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] In the cystic fibrosis transmembrane regulator (CFTR) and in the sulfonylurea receptor (SUR), ATP hydrolysis is associated with the regulation of opening and closing of ion channels carried by the ABC protein itself or other proteins.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Human ABC transporters are involved in several diseases that arise from polymorphisms in ABC genes and rarely due to complete loss of function of single ABC proteins.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The human ABCB (MDR/TAP) family is responsible for multiple drug resistance (MDR) against a variety of structurally unrelated drugs.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] ABCB1 or MDR1 P-glycoprotein is also involved in other biological processes for which lipid transport is the main function.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] It is found to mediate the secretion of the steroid aldosterone by the adrenals, and its inhibition blocked the migration of dendritic immune cells, possibly related to the outward transport of the lipid platelet activating factor (PAF).
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] It has also been reported that ABCB1 mediates transport of cortisol and dexamethasone, but not of progesterone in ABCB1 transfected cells.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] MDR1 can also transport cholesterol, short-chain and long-chain analogs of phosphatidylcholine (PC), phosphatidylethanolamine (PE), phosphatidylserine (PS), sphingomyelin (SM), and glucosylceramide (GlcCer).
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Multispecific transport of diverse endogenous lipids through the MDR1 transporter can possibly affect the transbilayer distribution of lipids, in particular of species normally predominant on the inner plasma membrane leaflet such as PS and PE.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] More recently, ABC-transporters have been shown to exist within the placenta, indicating they could play a protective role for the developing fetus against xenobiotics.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Evidence has shown that placental expression of the ABC-transporters P-glycoprotein (P-gp) and breast cancer resistance protein (BCRP) are increased in preterm compared to term placentae, with P-gp expression further increased in preterm pregnancies with chorioamnionitis.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] To a lesser extent, increasing maternal BMI also associated with increased placental ABC-transporter expression, but only at preterm.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] All ABC transport proteins share a structural organization consisting of four core domains.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] These domains consist of two trans-membrane (T) domains and two cytosolic (A) domains.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The two T domains alternate between an inward and outward facing orientation, and the alternation is powered by the hydrolysis of adenosine triphosphate or ATP.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] ATP binds to the A subunits and it is then hydrolyzed to power the alternation, but the exact process by which this happens is not known.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The four domains can be present in four separate polypeptides, which occur mostly in bacteria, or present in one or two multi-domain polypeptides.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] When the polypeptides are one domain, they can be referred to as a full domain, and when they are two multi-domains they can be referred to as a half domain.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The T domains are each built of typically 10 membrane spanning alpha helices, through which the transported substance can cross through the plasma membrane.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Also, the structure of the T domains determines the specificity of each ABC protein.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] In the inward facing conformation, the binding site on the A domain is open directly to the surrounding aqueous solutions.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] This allows hydrophilic molecules to enter the binding site directly from the inner leaflet of the phospholipid bilayer.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] In addition, a gap in the protein is accessible directly from the hydrophobic core of the inner leaflet of the membrane bilayer.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] This allows hydrophobic molecules to enter the binding site directly from the inner leaflet of the phospholipid bilayer.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] After the ATP powered move to the outward facing conformation, molecules are released from the binding site and allowed to escape into the exoplasmic leaflet or directly into the extracellular medium.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The common feature of all ABC transporters is that they consist of two distinct domains, the *transmembrane domain (TMD)* and the *nucleotide-binding domain (NBD)*.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The TMD, also known as membrane-spanning domain (MSD) or integral membrane (IM) domain, consists of alpha helices, embedded in the membrane bilayer.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] It recognizes a variety of substrates and undergoes conformational changes to transport the substrate across the membrane.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The sequence and architecture of TMDs is variable, reflecting the chemical diversity of substrates that can be translocated.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The NBD or ATP-binding cassette (ABC) domain, on the other hand, is located in the cytoplasm and has a highly conserved sequence.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] In most exporters, the N-terminal transmembrane domain and the C-terminal ABC domains are fused as a single polypeptide chain, arranged as TMD-NBD-TMD-NBD.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] An example is the *E. coli* hemolysin exporter HlyB.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Importers have an inverted organization, that is, NBD-TMD-NBD-TMD, where the ABC domain is N-terminal whereas the TMD is C-terminal, such as in the *E. coli* MacB protein responsible for macrolide resistance.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The structural architecture of ABC transporters consists minimally of two TMDs and two NBDs.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Four individual polypeptide chains including two TMD and two NBD subunits, may combine to form a *full transporter* such as in the *E. coli* BtuCD importer involved in the uptake of vitamin B12.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Most exporters, such as in the multidrug exporter Sav1866 from *Staphylococcus aureus*, are made up of a homodimer consisting of two *half transporters* or monomers of a TMD fused to a nucleotide-binding domain (NBD).
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] A full transporter is often required to gain functionality.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Some ABC transporters have additional elements that contribute to the regulatory function of this class of proteins.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] In particular, importers have a high-affinity *binding protein (BP)* that specifically associates with the substrate in the periplasm for delivery to the appropriate ABC transporter.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Exporters do not have the binding protein but have an *intracellular domain (ICD)* that joins the membrane-spanning helices and the ABC domain.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The ICD is believed to be responsible for communication between the TMD and NBD.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Most transporters have transmembrane domains that consist of a total of 12 α-helices with 6 α-helices per monomer.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Since TMDs are structurally diverse, some transporters have varying number of helices (between six and eleven).
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The TM domains are categorized into three distinct sets of folds: *type I ABC importer*, *type II ABC importer* and *ABC exporter* folds.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The classification of importer folds is based on detailed characterization of the sequences.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The type I ABC importer fold was originally observed in the ModB TM subunit of the molybdate transporter.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] This diagnostic fold can also be found in the MalF and MalG TM subunits of MalFGK2 and the Met transporter MetI.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] In the MetI transporter, a minimal set of 5 transmembrane helices constitute this fold while an additional helix is present for both ModB and MalG.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The common organization of the fold is the "up-down" topology of the TM2-5 helices that lines the translocation pathway and the TM1 helix wrapped around the outer, membrane-facing surface and contacts the other TM helices.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The type II ABC importer fold is observed in the twenty TM helix-domain of BtuCD and in Hi1471, a homologous transporter from *Haemophilus influenzae*.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] In BtuCD, the packing of the helices is complex.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The noticeable pattern is that the TM2 helix is positioned through the center of the subunit where it is surrounded in close proximity by the other helices.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Meanwhile, the TM5 and TM10 helices are positioned in the TMD interface.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The membrane spanning region of ABC exporters is organized into two "wings" that are composed of helices TM1 and TM2 from one subunit and TM3-6 of the other, in a domain-swapped arrangement.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] A prominent pattern is that helices TM1-3 are related to TM4-6 by an approximate twofold rotation around an axis in the plane of the membrane.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The exporter fold is originally observed in the Sav1866 structure.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] It contains 12 TM helices, 6 per monomer.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The ABC domain consists of two domains, the *catalytic core domain* similar to RecA-like motor ATPases and a smaller, structurally diverse *α-helical subdomain* that is unique to ABC transporters.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The larger domain typically consists of two β-sheets and six α helices, where the catalytic *Walker A motif* (GXXGXGKS/T where X is any amino acid) or *P-loop* and *Walker B motif* (ΦΦΦΦD, of which Φ is a hydrophobic residue) is situated.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The helical domain consists of three or four helices and the *ABC signature motif*, also known as *LSGGQ motif*, linker peptide or C motif.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The ABC domain also has a glutamine residue residing in a flexible loop called *Q loop*, lid or γ-phosphate switch, that connects the TMD and ABC.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The Q loop is presumed to be involved in the interaction of the NBD and TMD, particularly in the coupling of nucleotide hydrolysis to the conformational changes of the TMD during substrate translocation.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The *H motif* or switch region contains a highly conserved histidine residue that is also important in the interaction of the ABC domain with ATP.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The name ATP-binding cassette is derived from the diagnostic arrangement of the folds or motifs of this class of proteins upon formation of the ATP sandwich and ATP hydrolysis.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Dimer formation of the two ABC domains of transporters requires ATP binding.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] It is generally observed that the ATP bound state is associated with the most extensive interface between ABC domains, whereas the structures of nucleotide-free transporters exhibit conformations with greater separations between the ABC domains.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Structures of the ATP-bound state of isolated NBDs have been reported for importers including HisP, GlcV, MJ1267, *E. coli* MalK (E.c.MalK), *T. litoralis* MalK (TlMalK), and exporters such as TAP, HlyB, MJ0796, Sav1866, and MsbA.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] In these transporters, ATP is bound to the ABC domain.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Two molecules of ATP are positioned at the interface of the dimer, sandwiched between the Walker A motif of one subunit and the LSGGQ motif of the other.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] This was first observed in Rad50 and reported in structures of MJ0796, the NBD subunit of the LolD transporter from *Methanococcus jannaschii* and E.c.MalK of a maltose transporter.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] These structures were also consistent with results from biochemical studies revealing that ATP is in close contact with residues in the P-loop and LSGGQ motif during catalysis.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Nucleotide binding is required to ensure the electrostatic and/or structural integrity of the active site and contribute to the formation of an active NBD dimer.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] In addition, a residue that suggests the tight coupling of ATP binding and dimerization, is the conserved histidine in the H-loop.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] This histidine contacts residues across the dimer interface in the Walker A motif and the D loop, a conserved sequence following the Walker B motif.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The enzymatic hydrolysis of ATP requires proper binding of the phosphates and positioning of the γ-phosphate to the attacking water.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] In the nucleotide binding site, the oxygen atoms of the β- and γ-phosphates of ATP are stabilized by residues in the Walker A motif and coordinate with Mg2+.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] This Mg2+ ion also coordinates with the terminal aspartate residue in the Walker B motif through the attacking H2O.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] A general base, which may be the glutamate residue adjacent to the Walker B motif, glutamine in the Q-loop, or a histidine in the switch region that forms a hydrogen bond with the γ-phosphate of ATP, is found to catalyze the rate of ATP hydrolysis by promoting the attacking H2O.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The precise molecular mechanism of ATP hydrolysis is still controversial.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] ABC transporters are active transporters, that is, they use energy in the form of adenosine triphosphate (ATP) to translocate substrates across cell membranes.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] These proteins harness the energy of ATP binding and/or hydrolysis to drive conformational changes in the *transmembrane domain (TMD)* and consequently transport molecules.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] ABC importers and exporters have a common mechanism for transporting substrates.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The model that describes the conformational changes associated with the binding of the substrate is the *alternating-access model*.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] In this model, the substrate binding site alternates between *outward-* and *inward-facing conformations*.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The relative binding affinities of the two conformations for the substrate largely determines the net direction of transport.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] For importers, since translocation is directed from the periplasm to the cytoplasm, the outward-facing conformation has higher binding affinity for the substrate.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] In contrast, the substrate binding affinity in exporters is greater in the inward-facing conformation.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] A model that describes the conformational changes in the *nucleotide-binding domain (NBD)* as a result of ATP binding and hydrolysis is the *ATP-switch model*.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] This model presents two principal conformations of the NBDs: formation of a closed dimer upon binding two ATP molecules and dissociation to an open dimer facilitated by ATP hydrolysis and release of inorganic phosphate (Pi) and adenosine diphosphate (ADP).
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Switching between the open and closed dimer conformations induces conformational changes in the TMD resulting in substrate translocation.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The general mechanism for the transport cycle of ABC transporters has not been fully elucidated, but substantial structural and biochemical data has accumulated to support a model in which ATP binding and hydrolysis is coupled to conformational changes in the transporter.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The resting state of all ABC transporters has the NBDs in an open dimer configuration, with low affinity for ATP.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] This open conformation possesses a chamber accessible to the interior of the transporter.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The transport cycle is initiated by binding of substrate to the high-affinity site on the TMDs, which induces conformational changes in the NBDs and enhances the binding of ATP.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Two molecules of ATP bind, cooperatively, to form the closed dimer configuration.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The closed NBD dimer induces a conformational change in the TMDs such that the TMD opens, forming a chamber with an opening opposite to that of the initial state.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The affinity of the substrate to the TMD is reduced, thereby releasing the substrate.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Hydrolysis of ATP follows and then sequential release of Pi and then ADP restores the transporter to its basal configuration.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Although a common mechanism has been suggested, the order of substrate binding, nucleotide binding and hydrolysis, and conformational changes, as well as interactions between the domains is still debated.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Several groups studying ABC transporters have differing assumptions on the driving force of transporter function.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] It is generally assumed that ATP hydrolysis provides the principal energy input or "power stroke" for transport and that the NBDs operate alternately and are possibly involved in different steps in the transport cycle.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] However, recent structural and biochemical data shows that ATP binding, rather than ATP hydrolysis, provides the "power stroke".
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Some evidence to show that ATP binding is indeed the power stroke of the transport cycle was reported.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] It has been shown that ATP binding induces changes in the substrate-binding properties of the TMDs.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The affinity of ABC transporters for substrates has been difficult to measure directly, and indirect measurements, for instance through stimulation of ATPase activity, often reflects other rate-limiting steps.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Recently, direct measurement of vinblastine binding to permease-glycoprotein (P-glycoprotein) in the presence of nonhydrolyzable ATP analogs, e.g.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] 5'-adenylyl-β-γ-imidodiphosphate (AMP-PNP), showed that ATP binding, in the absence of hydrolysis, is sufficient to reduce substrate-binding affinity.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Also, ATP binding induces substantial conformational changes in the TMDs.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Spectroscopic, protease accessibility and crosslinking studies have shown that ATP binding to the NBDs induces conformational changes in multidrug resistance-associated protein-1 (MRP1), HisPMQ, LmrA, and Pgp.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Two dimensional crystal structures of AMP-PNP-bound Pgp showed that the major conformational change during the transport cycle occurs upon ATP binding and that subsequent ATP hydrolysis introduces more limited changes.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Rotation and tilting of transmembrane α-helices may both contribute to these conformational changes.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Other studies have focused on confirming that ATP binding induces NBD closed dimer formation.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Biochemical studies of intact transport complexes suggest that the conformational changes in the NBDs are relatively small.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] In the absence of ATP, the NBDs may be relatively flexible, but they do not involve a major reorientation of the NBDs with respect to the other domains.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] ATP binding induces a rigid body rotation of the two ABC subdomains with respect to each other, which allows the proper alignment of the nucleotide in the active site and interaction with the designated motifs.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] There is strong biochemical evidence that binding of two ATP molecules can be cooperative, that is, ATP must bind to the two active site pockets before the NBDs can dimerize and form the closed, catalytically active conformation.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Most ABC transporters that mediate the uptake of nutrients and other molecules in bacteria rely on a high-affinity solute binding protein (BP).
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] BPs are soluble proteins located in the periplasmic space between the inner and outer membranes of gram-negative bacteria.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Gram-positive microorganisms lack a periplasm such that their binding protein is often a lipoprotein bound to the external face of the cell membrane.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Some gram-positive bacteria have BPs fused to the transmembrane domain of the transporter itself.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The first successful x-ray crystal structure of an intact ABC importer is the molybdenum transporter (ModBC-A) from *Archaeoglobus fulgidus*.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Atomic-resolution structures of three other bacterial importers, *E. coli* BtuCD, *E. coli* maltose transporter (MalFGK2-E), and the putative metal-chelate transporter of *Haemophilus influenzae*, HI1470/1, have also been determined.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The structures provided detailed pictures of the interaction of the transmembrane and ABC domains as well as revealed two different conformations with an opening in two opposite directions.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Another common feature of importers is that each NBD is bound to one TMD primarily through a short cytoplasmic helix of the TMD, the "coupling helix".
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] This portion of the EAA loop docks in a surface cleft formed between the RecA-like and helical ABC subdomains and lies approximately parallel to the membrane bilayer.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The BtuCD and HI1470/1 are classified as large (Type II) ABC importers.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The transmembrane subunit of the vitamin B12 importer, BtuCD, contains 10 TM helices and the functional unit consists of two copies each of the nucleotide binding domain (NBD) and transmembrane domain (TMD).
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The TMD and NBD interact with one another via the cytoplasmic loop between two TM helices and the Q loop in the ABC.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] In the absence of nucleotide, the two ABC domains are folded and the dimer interface is open.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] A comparison of the structures with (BtuCDF) and without (BtuCD) binding protein reveals that BtuCD has an opening that faces the periplasm whereas in BtuCDF, the outward-facing conformation is closed to both sides of the membrane.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The structures of BtuCD and the BtuCD homolog, HI1470/1, represent two different conformational states of an ABC transporter.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The predicted translocation pathway in BtuCD is open to the periplasm and closed at the cytoplasmic side of the membrane while that of HI1470/1 faces the opposite direction and open only to the cytoplasm.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The difference in the structures is a 9° twist of one TM subunit relative to the other.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Structures of the ModBC-A and MalFGK2-E, which are in complex with their binding protein, correspond to small (Type I) ABC importers.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The TMDs of ModBC-A and MalFGK2-E have only six helices per subunit.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The homodimer of ModBC-A is in a conformation in which the TM subunits (ModB) orient in an inverted V-shape with a cavity accessible to the cytoplasm.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The ABC subunits (ModC), on the other hand, are arranged in an open, nucleotide-free conformation, in which the P-loop of one subunit faces but is detached from the LSGGQ motif of the other.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The binding protein ModA is in a closed conformation with substrate bound in a cleft between its two lobes and attached to the extracellular loops of ModB, wherein the substrate is sitting directly above the closed entrance of the transporter.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The MalFGK2-E structure resembles the catalytic transition state for ATP hydrolysis.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] It is in a closed conformation where it contains two ATP molecules, sandwiched between the Walker A and B motifs of one subunit and the LSGGQ motif of the other subunit.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The maltose binding protein (MBP or MalE) is docked on the periplasmic side of the TM subunits (MalF and MalG) and a large, occluded cavity can be found at the interface of MalF and MalG.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The arrangement of the TM helices is in a conformation that is closed toward the cytoplasm but with an opening that faces outward.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The structure suggests a possibility that MBP may stimulate the ATPase activity of the transporter upon binding.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The mechanism of transport for importers supports the alternating-access model.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The resting state of importers is inward-facing, where the nucleotide binding domain (NBD) dimer interface is held open by the TMDs and facing outward but occluded from the cytoplasm.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Upon docking of the closed, substrate-loaded binding protein towards the periplasmic side of the transmembrane domains, ATP binds and the NBD dimer closes.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] This switches the resting state of transporter into an outward-facing conformation, in which the TMDs have reoriented to receive substrate from the binding protein.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] After hydrolysis of ATP, the NBD dimer opens and substrate is released into the cytoplasm.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Release of ADP and Pi reverts the transporter into its resting state.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The only inconsistency of this mechanism to the ATP-switch model is that the conformation in its resting, nucleotide-free state is different from the expected outward-facing conformation.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Although that is the case, the key point is that the NBD does not dimerize unless ATP and binding protein is bound to the transporter.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Prokaryotic ABC exporters are abundant and have close homologues in eukaryotes.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] This class of transporters is studied based on the type of substrate that is transported.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] One class is involved in the protein (e.g. toxins, hydrolytic enzymes, S-layer proteins, lantibiotics, bacteriocins, and competence factors) export and the other in drug efflux.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] ABC transporters have gained extensive attention because they contribute to the resistance of cells to antibiotics and anticancer agents by pumping drugs out of the cells.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] A common mechanism is the overexpression of ABC exporters like P-glycoprotein (P-gp/ABCB1), multidrug resistance-associated protein 1 (MRP1/ABCC1), and breast cancer resistance protein (BCRP/ABCG2) in cancer cells that limit the exposure to anticancer drugs.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] In gram-negative organisms, ABC transporters mediate secretion of protein substrates across inner and outer membranes simultaneously without passing through the periplasm.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] This type of secretion is referred to as *type I secretion*, which involves three components that function in concert: an *ABC exporter*, a *membrane fusion protein (MFP)*, and an *outer membrane factor (OMF)*.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] An example is the secretion of hemolysin (HlyA) from *E. coli* where the inner membrane ABC transporter HlyB interacts with an inner membrane fusion protein HlyD and an outer membrane facilitator TolC.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] TolC allows hemolysin to be transported across the two membranes, bypassing the periplasm.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Bacterial drug resistance has become an increasingly major health problem.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] One of the mechanisms for drug resistance is associated with an increase in antibiotic efflux from the bacterial cell.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Drug resistance associated with drug efflux, mediated by P-glycoprotein, was originally reported in mammalian cells.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] In bacteria, Levy and colleagues presented the first evidence that antibiotic resistance was caused by active efflux of a drug.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] P-glycoprotein is the best-studied efflux pump and as such has offered important insights into the mechanism of bacterial pumps.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Although some exporters transport a specific type of substrate, most transporters extrude a diverse class of drugs with varying structure.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] These transporters are commonly called multi-drug resistant (MDR) ABC transporters and sometimes referred to as "hydrophobic vacuum cleaners".
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] P-glycoprotein (3.A.1.201.1) is a well-studied protein associated with multi-drug resistance.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] It belongs to the human *ABCB (MDR/TAP)* family and is also known as *ABCB1* or *MDR1 Pgp*.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] MDR1 consists of a functional monomer with two transmembrane domains (TMD) and two nucleotide-binding domains (NBD).
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] This protein can transport mainly cationic or electrically neutral substrates as well as a broad spectrum of amphiphilic substrates.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The structure of the full-size ABCB1 monomer was obtained in the presence and absence of nucleotide using electron cryo crystallography.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Without the nucleotide, the TMDs are approximately parallel and form a barrel surrounding a central pore, with the opening facing towards the extracellular side of the membrane and closed at the intracellular face.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] In the presence of the nonhydrolyzable ATP analog, AMP-PNP, the TMDs have a substantial reorganization with three clearly segregated domains.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] A central pore, which is enclosed between the TMDs, is slightly open towards the intracellular face with a gap between two domains allowing access of substrate from the lipid phase.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Substantial repacking and possible rotation of the TM helices upon nucleotide binding suggests a helix rotation model for the transport mechanism.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The genome of the model plant *Arabidopsis thaliana* is capable of encoding 120 ABC proteins compared to 50-70 ABC proteins that are encoded by the human genome and fruit flies (*Drosophila melanogaster*).
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Plant ABC proteins are categorized in 13 subfamilies on the basis of size (full, half or quarter), orientation, and overall amino acid sequence similarity.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Multidrug resistant (MDR) homologs, also known as P-glycoproteins, represent the largest subfamily in plants with 22 members and the second largest overall ABC subfamily.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The B subfamily of plant ABC transporters (ABCBs) are characterized by their localization to the plasma membrane.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Plant ABCB transporters are characterized by heterologously expressing them in *Escherichia coli*, *Saccharomyces cerevisiae*, *Schizosaccharomyces pombe* (fission yeast), and HeLa cells to determine substrate specificity.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Plant ABCB transporters have shown to transport the phytohormone indole-3-acetic acid ( IAA), also known as auxin, the essential regulator for plant growth and development.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The directional polar transport of auxin mediates plant environmental responses through processes such as phototropism and gravitropism.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The first high-resolution structure reported for an ABC exporter was that of Sav1866 (3.A.1.106.2) from *Staphylococcus aureus*.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Sav1866 is a homolog of multidrug ABC transporters.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] It shows significant sequence similarity to human ABC transporters of subfamily B that includes MDR1 and TAP1/TAP2.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The ATPase activity of Sav1866 is known to be stimulated by cancer drugs such as doxorubicin, vinblastine and others, which suggests similar substrate specificity to P-glycoprotein and therefore a possible common mechanism of substrate translocation.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Sav1866 is a homodimer of half transporters, and each subunit contains an N-terminal TMD with six helices and a C-terminal NBD.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The NBDs are similar in structure to those of other ABC transporters, in which the two ATP binding sites are formed at the dimer interface between the Walker A motif of one NBD and the LSGGQ motif of the other.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The ADP-bound structure of Sav1866 shows the NBDs in a closed dimer and the TM helices split into two "wings" oriented towards the periplasm, forming the outward-facing conformation.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Each wing consists of helices TM1-2 from one subunit and TM3-6 from the other subunit.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] It contains long intracellular loops (ICLs or ICD) connecting the TMDs that extend beyond the lipid bilayer into the cytoplasm and interacts with the 8=D.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Whereas the importers contain a short coupling helix that contact a single NBD, Sav1866 has two intracellular coupling helices, one (ICL1) contacting the NBDs of both subunits and the other (ICL2) interacting with only the opposite NBD subunit.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] MsbA (3.A.1.106.1) is a multi-drug resistant (MDR) ABC transporter and possibly a lipid flippase.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] It is an ATPase that transports lipid A, the hydrophobic moiety of lipopolysaccharide (LPS), a glucosamine-based saccharolipid that makes up the outer monolayer of the outer membranes of most gram-negative bacteria.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Lipid A is an endotoxin and so loss of MsbA from the cell membrane or mutations that disrupt transport results in the accumulation of lipid A in the inner cell membrane resulting to cell death.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] It is a close bacterial homolog of P-glycoprotein (Pgp) by protein sequence homology and has overlapping substrate specificities with the MDR-ABC transporter LmrA from *Lactococcus lactis*.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] MsbA from *E. coli* is 36% identical to the NH2-terminal half of human MDR1, suggesting a common mechanism for transport of amphiphatic and hydrophobic substrates.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The MsbA gene encodes a half transporter that contains a transmembrane domain (TMD) fused with a nucleotide-binding domain (NBD).
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] It is assembled as a homodimer with a total molecular mass of 129.2 kD.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] MsbA contains 6 TMDs on the periplasmic side, an NBD located on the cytoplasmic side of the cell membrane, and an intracellular domain (ICD), bridging the TMD and NBD.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] This conserved helix extending from the TMD segments into or near the active site of the NBD is largely responsible for crosstalk between TMD and NBD.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] In particular, ICD1 serves as a conserved pivot about which the NBD can rotate, therefore allowing the NBD to disassociate and dimerize during ATP binding and hydrolysis.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Previously published (and now retracted) X-ray structures of MsbA were inconsistent with the bacterial homolog Sav1866.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The structures were reexamined and found to have an error in the assignment of the hand resulting to incorrect models of MsbA.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Recently, the errors have been rectified and new structures have been reported.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The resting state of *E. coli* MsbA exhibits an inverted "V" shape with a chamber accessible to the interior of the transporter suggesting an *open, inward-facing conformation*.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The dimer contacts are concentrated between the extracellular loops and while the NBDs are ≈50Å apart, the subunits are facing each other.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The distance between the residues in the site of the dimer interface have been verified by cross-linking experiments and EPR spectroscopy studies.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The relatively large chamber allows it to accommodate large head groups such as that present in lipid A.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Significant conformational changes are required to move the large sugar head groups across the membrane.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The difference between the two nucleotide-free (apo) structures is the ≈30° pivot of TM4/TM5 helices relative to the TM3/TM6 helices.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] In the closed apo state (from *V. cholerae* MsbA), the NBDs are aligned and although closer, have not formed an ATP sandwich, and the P loops of opposing monomers are positioned next to one another.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] In comparison to the open conformation, the dimer interface of the TMDs in the *closed, inward-facing conformation* has extensive contacts.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] For both apo conformations of MsbA, the chamber opening is facing inward.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The structure of MsbA-AMP-PNP (5'-adenylyl-β-γ-imidodiphosphate), obtained from *S. typhimurium*, is similar to Sav1866.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The NBDs in this *nucleotide-bound, outward-facing conformation*, come together to form a canonical ATP dimer sandwich, that is, the nucleotide is situated in between the P-loop and LSGGQ motif.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The conformational transition from MsbA-closed-apo to MsbA-AMP-PNP involves two steps, which are more likely concerted: a ≈10° pivot of TM4/TM5 helices towards TM3/TM6, bringing the NBDs closer but not into alignment followed by tilting of TM4/TM5 helices ≈20° out of plane.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The twisting motion results in the separation of TM3/TM6 helices away from TM1/TM2 leading to a change from an inward- to an outward- facing conformation.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Thus, changes in both the orientation and spacing of the NBDs dramatically rearrange the packing of transmembrane helices and effectively switch access to the chamber from the inner to the outer leaflet of the membrane.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The structures determined for MsbA is basis for the tilting model of transport.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The structures described also highlight the dynamic nature of ABC exporters as also suggested by fluorescence and EPR studies.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Recent work has resulted in the discovery of MsbA inhibitors.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] ABC exporters have a transport mechanism that is consistent with both the alternating-access model and ATP-switch model.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] In the apo states of exporters, the conformation is inward-facing and the TMDs and NBDs are relatively far apart to accommodate amphiphilic or hydrophobic substrates.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] For MsbA, in particular, the size of the chamber is large enough to accommodate the sugar groups from lipopolysaccharides (LPS).
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] As has been suggested by several groups, binding of substrate initiates the transport cycle.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The "power stroke", that is, ATP binding that induces NBD dimerization and formation of the ATP sandwich, drives the conformational changes in the TMDs.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] In MsbA, the sugar head groups are sequestered within the chamber during the "power stroke".
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The cavity is lined with charged and polar residues that are likely solvated creating an energetically unfavorable environment for hydrophobic substrates and energetically favorable for polar moieties in amphiphilic compounds or sugar groups from LPS.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Since the lipid cannot be stable for a long time in the chamber environment, lipid A and other hydrophobic molecules may "flip" into an energetically more favorable position within the outer membrane leaflet.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The "flipping" may also be driven by the rigid-body shearing of the TMDs while the hydrophobic tails of the LPS are dragged through the lipid bilayer.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Repacking of the helices switches the conformation into an outward-facing state.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] ATP hydrolysis may widen the periplasmic opening and push the substrate towards the outer leaflet of the lipid bilayer.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Hydrolysis of the second ATP molecule and release of Pi separates the NBDs followed by restoration of the resting state, opening the chamber towards the cytoplasm for another cycle.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] ABC transporters are known to play a crucial role in the development of multidrug resistance (MDR).
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] In MDR, patients that are on medication eventually develop resistance not only to the drug they are taking but also to several different types of drugs.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] This is caused by several factors, one of which is increased expulsion of the drug from the cell by ABC transporters.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] For example, the ABCB1 protein (P-glycoprotein) functions in pumping tumor suppression drugs out of the cell.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Pgp also called MDR1, ABCB1, is the prototype of ABC transporters and also the most extensively-studied gene.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Pgp is known to transport organic cationic or neutral compounds.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] A few ABCC family members, also known as MRP, have also been demonstrated to confer MDR to organic anion compounds.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The most-studied member in ABCG family is ABCG2, also known as BCRP (breast cancer resistance protein) confer resistance to most Topoisomerase I or II inhibitors such as topotecan, irinotecan, and doxorubicin.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] It is unclear exactly how these proteins can translocate such a wide variety of drugs, however, one model (the hydrophobic vacuum cleaner model) states that, in P-glycoprotein, the drugs are bound indiscriminately from the lipid phase based on their hydrophobicity.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The Discovery of the first eukaryotic ABC transporter protein came from studies on tumor cells and cultured cells that exhibited resistance to several drugs with unrelated chemical structures.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] These cells were shown to express elevated levels of multidrug-resistance (MDR) transport protein which was originally called P-glycoprotein (P-gp), but it is also referred to as multidrug resistance protein 1 (MDR1) or ABCB1.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] This protein uses ATP hydrolysis, just like the other ABC transporters, to export a large variety of drugs from the cytosol to the extracellular medium.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] In multidrug-resistant cells, the MDR1 gene is frequently amplified.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] This results in a large overproduction of the MDR1 protein.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The substrates of mammalian ABCB1 are primarily planar, lipid-soluble molecules with one or more positive charges.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] All of these substrates compete with one another for transport, suggesting that they bind to the same or overlapping sites on the protein.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Many of the drugs that are transported out by ABCB1 are small, nonpolar drugs that diffuse across the extracellular medium into the cytosol, where they block various cellular functions.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Drugs such as colchicine and vinblastine, which block assembly of microtubules, freely cross the membrane into the cytosol, but the export of these drugs by ABCB1 reduces their concentration in the cell.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Therefore, it takes a higher concentration of the drugs is required to kill the cells that express ABCB1 than those that do not express the gene.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Other ABC transporters that contribute to multidrug resistance are ABCC1 (MRP1) and ABCG2 (breast cancer resistance protein).
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] To solve the problems associated with multidrug-resistance by MDR1, different types of drugs can be used or the ABC transporters themselves must be inhibited.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] For other types of drugs to work, they must bypass the resistance mechanism, which is the ABC transporter.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] To do this other anticancer drugs can be utilized such as alkylating drugs (cyclophosphamide), antimetabolites (5-fluorouracil), and the anthracycline modified drugs (annamycin and doxorubicin-peptide).
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] These drugs would not function as a substrate of ABC transporters, and would thus not be transported.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The other option is to use a combination of ABC inhibitory drugs and anticancer drugs at the same time.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] This would reverse the resistance to the anticancer drugs so that they could function as intended.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The substrates that reverse the resistance to anticancer drugs are called chemosensitizers.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Drug resistance is a common clinical problem that occurs in patients with infectious diseases and in patients with cancer.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Prokaryotic and eukaryotic microorganisms as well as neoplastic cells are often found to be resistant to drugs.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] MDR is frequently associated with overexpression of ABC transporters.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Inhibition of ABC transporters by low-molecular weight compounds has been extensively investigated in cancer patients; however, the clinical results have been disappointing.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] Recently various RNAi strategies have been applied to reverse MDR in different tumor models and this technology is effective in reversing ABC-transporter-mediated MDR in cancer cells and is therefore a promising strategy for overcoming MDR by gene therapeutic applications.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] RNAi technology could also be considered for overcoming MDR in infectious diseases caused by microbial pathogens.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] In addition to conferring MDR in tumor cells, ABC transporters are also expressed in the membranes of healthy cells, where they facilitate the transport of various endogenous substances, as well as of substances foreign to the body.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] For instance, ABC transporters such as Pgp, the MRPs and BCRP limit the absorption of many drugs from the intestine, and pump drugs from the liver cells to the bile as a means of removing foreign substances from the body.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] A large number of drugs are either transported by ABC transporters themselves or affect the transport of other drugs.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p01] The latter scenario can lead to drug-drug interactions, sometimes resulting in altered effects of the drugs.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] There are a number of assay types that allow the detection of ABC transporter interactions with endogenous and xenobiotic compounds.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] The complexity of assay range from relatively simple membrane assays. like vesicular transport assay, ATPase assay to more complex cell based assays up to intricate *in vivo**Jeffrey P, Summerfield SG (2007).
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] "Challenges for blood-brain barrier (BBB) screening".
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] The *vesicular transport assay* detects the translocation of molecules by ABC transporters.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] Membranes prepared under suitable conditions contain inside-out oriented vesicles with the ATP binding site and substrate binding site of the transporter facing the buffer outside.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] Substrates of the transporter are taken up into the vesicles in an ATP dependent manner.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] Rapid filtration using glass fiber filters or nitrocellulose membranes are used to separate the vesicles from the incubation solution and the test compound trapped inside the vesicles is retained on the filter.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] The quantity of the transported unlabelled molecules is determined by HPLC, LC/MS, LC/MS/MS.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] Alternatively, the compounds are radiolabeled, fluorescent or have a fluorescent tag so that the radioactivity or fluorescence retained on the filter can be quantified.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] Various types of membranes from different sources (e.g. insect cells, transfected or selected mammalian cell lines) are used in vesicular transport studies.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] Membranes are commercially available or can be prepared from various cells or even tissues e.g. liver canalicular membranes.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] This assay type has the advantage of measuring the actual disposition of the substrate across the cell membrane.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] Its disadvantage is that compounds with medium-to-high passive permeability are not retained inside the vesicles making direct transport measurements with this class of compounds difficult to perform.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] The vesicular transport assay can be performed in an "indirect" setting, where interacting test drugs modulate the transport rate of a reporter compound.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] This assay type is particularly suitable for the detection of possible drug-drug interactions and drug-endogenous substrate interactions.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] It is not sensitive to the passive permeability of the compounds and therefore detects all interacting compounds.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] Yet, it does not provide information on whether the compound tested is an inhibitor of the transporter, or a substrate of the transporter inhibiting its function in a competitive fashion.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] A typical example of an indirect vesicular transport assay is the detection of the inhibition of taurocholate transport by ABCB11 (BSEP).
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] Efflux transporter-expressing cells actively pump substrates out of the cell, which results in a lower rate of substrate accumulation, lower intracellular concentration at steady state, or a faster rate of substrate elimination from cells loaded with the substrate.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] Transported radioactive substrates or labeled fluorescent dyes can be directly measured, or in an indirect set up, the modulation of the accumulation of a probe substrate (e.g. fluorescent dyes like rhodamine 123, or calcein) can be determined in the presence of a test drug.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] Calcein-AM, A highly permeable derivative of calcein readily penetrates into intact cells, where the endogenous esterases rapidly hydrolyze it to the fluorescent calcein.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] In contrast to calcein-AM, calcein has low permeability and therefore gets trapped in the cell and accumulates.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] As calcein-AM is an excellent substrate of the MDR1 and MRP1 efflux transporters, cells expressing MDR1 and/or MRP1 transporters pump the calcein-AM out of the cell before esterases can hydrolyze it.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] This results in a lower cellular accumulation rate of calcein.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] The higher the MDR activity is in the cell membrane, the less Calcein is accumulated in the cytoplasm.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] In MDR-expressing cells, the addition of an MDR inhibitor or an MDR substrate in excess dramatically increases the rate of Calcein accumulation.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] Activity of multidrug transporter is reflected by the difference between the amounts of dye accumulated in the presence and the absence of inhibitor.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] Using selective inhibitors, transport activity of MDR1 and MRP1 can be easily distinguished.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] This assay can be used to screen drugs for transporter interactions, and also to quantify the MDR activity of cells.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] The calcein assay is the proprietary assay of SOLVO Biotechnology.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] There are 49 known ABC transporters present in humans, which are classified into seven families by the Human Genome Organization.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] A full list of human ABC transporters can be found from.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] The ABCA subfamily is composed of 12 full transporters split into two subgroups.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] The first subgroup consists of seven genes that map to six different chromosomes.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] These are ABCA1, ABCA2, ABCA3, and ABCA4, ABCA7, ABCA12, and ABCA13.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] The other subgroup consists of ABCA5 and ABCA6 and ABCA8, ABCA9 and ABCA10.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] All of subgroup 2 is organized into a head to tail cluster of chromosomes on chromosome 17q24.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] Genes in this second subgroup are distinguished from ABCA1-like genes by having 37-38 exons as opposed to the 50 exons in ABCA1.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] The ABCA1 subgroup is implicated in the development of genetic diseases.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] In the recessive Tangier's disease, the ABCA1 protein is mutated.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] Also, the ABCA4 maps to a region of chromosome 1p21 that contains the gene for Stargardt's disease.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] This gene is found to be highly expressed in rod photoreceptors and is mutated in Stargardt's disease, recessive retinitis pigmentism, and the majority of recessive cone-rod dystrophy.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] The ABCB subfamily is composed of four full transporters and two half transporters.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] This is the only human subfamily to have both half and full types of transporters.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] ABCB1 was discovered as a protein overexpressed in certain drug resistant tumor cells.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] It is expressed primarily in the blood–brain barrier and liver and is thought to be involved in protecting cells from toxins.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] Cells that overexpress this protein exhibit multi-drug resistance.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] Subfamily ABCC contains thirteen members and nine of these transporters are referred to as the Multidrug Resistance Proteins (MRPs).
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] The MRP proteins are found throughout nature and they mediate many important functions.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] They are known to be involved in ion transport, toxin secretion, and signal transduction.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] Of the nine MRP proteins, four of them, MRP4, 5, 8, 9, (ABCC4, 5, 11, and 12), have a typical ABC structure with four domains, comprising two membrane spanning domains, with each spanning domain followed by a nucleotide binding domain.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] The remaining 5 MRP's (MRP1, 2, 6, 7) (ABCC1, 2, 3, 6 and 10) are known as long MRPs and feature an additional fifth domain at their N terminus.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] CFTR, the transporter involved in the disease cystic fibrosis, is also considered part of this subfamily.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] Cystic fibrosis occurs upon mutation and loss of function of CFTR.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] The sulfonylurea receptors (SUR), involved in insulin secretion, neuronal function, and muscle function, are also part of this family of proteins.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] Mutations in SUR proteins are a potential cause of Neonatal diabetes mellitus.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] SUR is also the binding site for drugs such as sulfonylureas and potassium-channel openers activators such as diazoxide.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] The ABCD subfamily consists of four genes that encode half transporters expressed exclusively in the peroxisome.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] ABCD1 is responsible for the X-linked form of Adrenoleukodystrophy (ALD) which is a disease characterized by neurodegeneration and adrenal deficiency that typically is initiated in late childhood.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] The cells of ALD patients feature accumulation of unbranched saturated fatty acids, but the exact role of ABCD1 in the process is still undetermined.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] In addition, the function of other ABCD genes have yet to be determined but have been thought to exert related functions in fatty acid metabolism.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] Both of these subgroups are composed of genes that have ATP binding domains that are closely related to other ABC transporters, but these genes do not encode for trans-membrane domains.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] ABCE consists of only one member, OABP or ABCE1, which is known to recognize certain oligodendrocytes produced in response to certain viral infections.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] Each member of the ABCF subgroup consist of a pair of ATP binding domains.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] Six half transporters with ATP binding sites on the N terminus and trans-membrane domains at the C terminus make up the ABCG subfamily.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] This orientation is opposite of all other ABC genes.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] There are only 5 ABCG genes in the human genome, but there are 15 in the Drosophila genome and 10 in yeast.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] The ABCG2 gene was discovered in cell lines selected for high level resistance for mitoxantrone and no expression of ABCB1 or ABCC1.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] ABCG2 can export anthracycline anticancer drugs, as well as topotecan, mitoxantrone, or doxorubicin as substrates.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] Chromosomal translocations have been found to cause the ABCG2 amplification or rearrangement found in resistant cell lines.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] The following classification system for transmembrane solute transporters has been constructed in the TCDB.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] Three families of ABC exporters are defined by their evolutionary origins.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] ABC1 exporters evolved by intragenic triplication of a 2 TMS precursor (TMS = transmembrane segment.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] A "2 TMS" protein has 2 transmembrane segments) to give 6 TMS proteins.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] ABC2 exporters evolved by intragenic duplication of a 3 TMS precursor, and ABC3 exporters evolved from a 4 TMS precursor which duplicated either extragenicly to give two 4 TMS proteins, both required for transport function, or intragenicly to give 8 or 10 TMS proteins.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] The 10 TMS proteins appear to have two extra TMSs between the two 4 TMS repeat units.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] Most uptake systems (all except 3.A.1.21) are of the ABC2 type, divided into type I and type II by the way they handle nucleotides.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] A special subfamily of ABC2 importers called ECF use a separate subunit for substrate recognition.
[src:lipid/abc-transporter-p02] Many structures of water-soluble domains of ABC proteins have been produced in recent years.
[src:lipid/abca1] It was discovered that a mutation in the ABCA1 protein is responsible for causing Tangier disease by several groups in 1998.
[src:lipid/abca1] Gerd Schmitz's group in Germany and Michael Hayden's group in British Columbia were using standard genetics techniques and DNA from family pedigrees to locate the mutation.
[src:lipid/abca1] Richard Lawn's group at CV Therapeutics in Palo Alto, CA used cDNA microarrays, which were relatively new at the time, to assess gene expression profiles from cell lines created from normal and affected individuals.
[src:lipid/abca1] They showed cell lines from patients with Tangier's disease showed differential regulation of the ABCA1 gene.
[src:lipid/abca1] Subsequent sequencing of the gene identified the mutations.
[src:lipid/abca1] This group received an award from the American Heart Association for their discovery.
[src:lipid/abca1] Tangier disease has been identified in nearly 100 patients worldwide, and patients have a broad range of biochemical and clinical phenotypes as over 100 different mutations have been identified in ABCA1 resulting in the disease.
[src:lipid/abca1] The membrane-associated protein encoded by this gene is a member of the superfamily of ATP-binding cassette (ABC) transporters.
[src:lipid/abca1] ABC proteins transport various molecules across extra- and intracellular membranes.
[src:lipid/abca1] ABC genes are divided into seven distinct subfamilies (ABCA, MDR/TAP, MRP, ALD, OABP, GCN20, White).
[src:lipid/abca1] This protein is a member of the ABCA subfamily.
[src:lipid/abca1] Members of the ABCA subfamily comprise the only major ABC subfamily found exclusively in multicellular eukaryotes.
[src:lipid/abca1] With cholesterol as its substrate, this protein functions as a cholesterol efflux pump in the cellular lipid removal pathway.
[src:lipid/abca1] While the complete 3D-structure of ABCA1 remains relatively unknown, there has been some determination of the c-terminus.
[src:lipid/abca1] The ABCA1 c-terminus contains a PDZ domain, responsible for mediating protein-protein interactions, as well as a VFVNFA motif essential for lipid efflux activity.
[src:lipid/abca1] ABCA1 mediates the efflux of cholesterol and phospholipids to lipid-poor apolipoproteins (apoA1 and apoE) (reverse cholesterol transport), which then form nascent high-density lipoproteins (HDL).
[src:lipid/abca1] It also mediates the transport of lipids between Golgi and cell membrane.
[src:lipid/abca1] Since this protein is needed throughout the body it is expressed ubiquitously as a 220 kDa protein.
[src:lipid/abca1] It is present in higher quantities in tissues that shuttle or are involved in the turnover of lipids such as the liver, the small intestine and adipose tissue.
[src:lipid/abca1] Factors that act upon the ABCA1 transporter's expression or its posttranslational modification are also molecules that are involved in its subsequent function like fatty acids, cholesterol and also cytokines and cAMP.
[src:lipid/abca1] Adiponectin induces reverse cholesterol transport by an ABCA1-dependent pathway.
[src:lipid/abca1] Other endogenous metabolites more loosely related to the ABCA1 functions are also reported to influence the expression of this transporter, including glucose and bilirubin.
[src:lipid/abca1] Overexpression of ABCA1 has been reported to induce resistance to the anti-inflammatory diarylheptanoid antioxidant curcumin.
[src:lipid/abca1] Human data from patients and controls were used to demonstrate the translation of mouse findings in human disease.
[src:lipid/abca1] Mutations in this gene have been associated with Tangier disease and familial high-density lipoprotein deficiency.
[src:lipid/abca1] ABCA1 has been shown to be reduced in Tangier disease which features physiological deficiencies of HDL.
[src:lipid/abca1] Leukocytes' *ABCA1* gene expression is upregulated in postmenopausal women receiving hormone replacement therapy (HRT).
[src:lipid/abca1] ABCA1 expression is also upregulated in tumor-associated astroctytes surrounding glioblastoma brain tumors, and is important to the tumor progression.
[src:lipid/abcg5] The protein encoded by this gene is a member of the superfamily of ATP-binding cassette (ABC) transporters.
[src:lipid/abcg5] ABC proteins transport various molecules across extra- and intra-cellular membranes.
[src:lipid/abcg5] ABC genes are divided into seven distinct subfamilies (ABC1, MDR/TAP, MRP, ALD, OABP, GCN20, White).
[src:lipid/abcg5] This protein is a member of the White subfamily.
[src:lipid/abcg5] The protein encoded by this gene functions as a half-transporter to limit intestinal absorption and promote biliary excretion of sterols.
[src:lipid/abcg5] It is expressed in a tissue-specific manner in the liver, colon, and intestine.
[src:lipid/abcg5] This gene is tandemly arrayed on chromosome 2, in a head-to-head orientation with family member ABCG8.
[src:lipid/abcg5] Mutations in this gene may contribute to sterol accumulation and atherosclerosis, and have been observed in patients with sitosterolemia.
[src:lipid/abcg8] This gene is tandemly arrayed on chromosome 2, in a head-to-head orientation with family member ABCG5.
[src:lipid/abcg8] A loss-of-function mutation in ABCG8 impairs the removal of sterols from cells and, in the homozygous case, leads to sitosterolemia.
[src:lipid/abcg8] Heterozygous individuals show slightly increased sterol absorption, normal cholesterol levels, and slightly elevated phytosterol levels.
[src:lipid/abcg8] A gain-of-function SNP rs11887534 increases the likelihood of gallbladder disease, especially cholesterol gallstones.
[src:lipid/abcg8] This is probably because more cholesterol is pumped into the bile lumen.
[src:lipid/apoa4] APOA4 resides on chromosome 11 in close linkage to APOA1 and APOC3.
[src:lipid/apoa4] APOA4 contains 3 exons separated by two introns, and is polymorphic, although most of the reported sequence polymorphisms occur in exon 3.
[src:lipid/apoa4] The best validated and studied non-synonymous SNPs are a glutamine → histidine substitution at codon 360 and a threonine → serine substitution at codon 347; a sequence polymorphism has also been identified in the 3'UTR of the third exon.
[src:lipid/apoa4] Intra-species comparative gene sequence analysis suggests that the APOA4 gene arose from APOA1 by gene duplication approximately 270 MYA.
[src:lipid/apoa4] The primary translation product of the APOA4 gene is a 396-residue preprotein, which undergoes proteolytic processing to yield apo A-IV, a 376-residue mature O-linked glycoprotein.
[src:lipid/apoa4] In most mammals, including humans, apo A-IV synthesis is confined to the intestine; however in mice and rats hepatic synthesis also occurs.
[src:lipid/apoa4] Apo A-IV is secreted into circulation on the surface of newly synthesized chylomicron particles.
[src:lipid/apoa4] Intestinal fat absorption dramatically increases the synthesis and secretion of apo A-IV.
[src:lipid/apoa4] Human apo A-IV deficiency has not been reported.
[src:lipid/apoa4] APOA4 has been shown to interact with GPLD1.
[src:lipid/apoa5] The gene for apolipoprotein A5 (APOA5, gene ID 116519, OMIM accession number – 606368) was originally found by comparative sequencing of human and mice DNA as a last member of the gene cluster of apolipoproteins APOA1/APOC3/APOA4/APOA5, located on human chromosome 11 at position 11q23.
[src:lipid/apoa5] The creation of two mice models (APOA5 transgenic and APOA5 knock-out) confirmed the important role of this gene in plasma triglyceride determination.
[src:lipid/apoa5] The transgenic mice had lower and the knock-out mice higher levels of plasma triglycerides, while plasma cholesterol levels remained unchanged in both animal models.
[src:lipid/apoa5] A Dutch group simultaneously described an identical gene as apolipoprotein which it is associated with the early phase of liver regeneration, but failed to recognise its important role in the determination of plasma triglyceride levels.
[src:lipid/apoa5] The *APOA5* gene resides on chromosome 11 at the band 11q23 and contains 4 exons and 3 introns.
[src:lipid/apoa5] This gene uses alternate polyadenylation sites and is located proximal to the apolipoprotein gene cluster on chromosome 11q23.
[src:lipid/apoa5] This protein belongs to the apolipoprotein A1/A4/E family and contains 2 coiled coil domains.
[src:lipid/apoa5] Overall, APOA5 is predicted to have approximately 60% a-helical content.
[src:lipid/apoa5] The mature APOA5 protein spans a length of 366 amino acid residues, of which 23 amino acids code for the signal peptide.
[src:lipid/apoa5] The molecular mass of the precursor was calculated to be 41 kDa, while the mature APOA5 protein was calculated to be 39 kDa.
[src:lipid/apoa5] In humans, APOA5 is expressed almost exclusively in the liver tissue; some minor expressions have also been detected in the small intestine.
[src:lipid/apoa5] Nothing is known about the existence of the potential alternative splicing variants of this gene.
[src:lipid/apoa5] In comparison with other apolipoproteins, plasma concentration of APOA5 is very low (less than 1 μg/mL).
[src:lipid/apoa5] This suggests that it has more catalytic than structural functions, since there is less than one APOA5 molecule per one lipoprotein particle.
[src:lipid/apoa5] APOA5 is associated predominantly with TG-rich lipoproteins (chylomicrons and VLDL) and has also been detected on HDL particles.
[src:lipid/apoa5] APOA5 mainly functions to influence plasma triglyceride levels.
[src:lipid/apoa5] The first suggested mechanism supposes that APOA5 functions as an activator of lipoprotein lipase (which is a key enzyme in triglyceride catabolism) and, through this process, enhances the metabolism of TG-rich particles.
[src:lipid/apoa5] The second is the possible effect of APOA5 on the secretion of VLDL particles, since APOA5 reduces hepatic production by inhibiting VLDL-particle production and assembly by binding to cellular membranes and lipids.
[src:lipid/apoa5] Finally, the third possibility relates to the acceleration of the hepatic uptake of lipoprotein remnants and it has been shown that APOA5 binds to different members of the low-density lipoprotein receptor family.
[src:lipid/apoa5] In addition to its TG-lowering effect, APOA5 also plays a significant role in modulating HDL maturation and cholesterol metabolism.
[src:lipid/apoa5] Increased APOA5 levels were associated with skewed cholesterol distribution from VLDL to large HDL particles.
[src:lipid/apoa5] APOA5 mRNA is upregulated during liver regeneration and this suggests that APOA5 serves a function in hepatocyte proliferation.
[src:lipid/apoa5] It's also reported that APOA5 could enhance insulin secretion in beta-cells and the cell surface midkine could be involved in APOA5 endocytosis.
[src:lipid/apoa5] Within the APOA5 gene, a couple of important SNPs with a widely confirmed effect on plasma TG levels as well as rare mutations have been described.
[src:lipid/apoa5] There are also a further three common variants (A-3>G, IVS+476 G>A and T1259>C) which are not necessary for haplotype characterisation.
[src:lipid/apoa5] Population frequencies of common APOA5 alleles exhibit large interethnic differences.
[src:lipid/apoa5] For example, there are about 15% of carriers of the rs66299(C) allele among Caucasians, but the frequency could reach even between 40% and 50% among Asians.
[src:lipid/apoa5] In contrast, the Trp19 allele is very rare in the Asian population (less than 1% of carriers) but is common in Caucasians (about 15% of carriers).
[src:lipid/apoa5] Vice versa, important SNP (rs2075291, G553T, Gly185>Cys) with a population frequency of about 5% has been detected among Asians, but it is extremely rare among Caucasians.
[src:lipid/apoa5] Sporadic publications refer to some other common polymorphisms, e.g.
[src:lipid/apoa5] Val153>Met (rs3135507, G457A) and also suggest significant sex-dependent associations with plasma lipids.
[src:lipid/apoa5] Rare variants within the APOA5 gene have been described in a couple of different populations.
[src:lipid/apoa5] Among the "common mutations/rare SNPs", one of the most characterised on a population level is the Ala315>Val exchange.
[src:lipid/apoa5] Originally detected in patients with extreme TG levels over 10 mmol/L, it was also found in about 0.7% of the general population (mostly in individuals with normal TG values), which suggests a low penetrance of this variant.
[src:lipid/apoa5] More than twenty other rare variants (mutations) have been described within the human APOA5 gene.
[src:lipid/apoa5] They cover a wide spectrum that includes premature stop codons, amino acid changes as well as insertions and deletions.
[src:lipid/apoa5] These mutations are generally associated with hypertriglyceridaemia, but penetration is usually not 100%.
[src:lipid/apoa5] Individual mutations have been found mostly in one pedigree only.
[src:lipid/apoa5] Not all the SNPs have a detrimental effect on TG levels.
[src:lipid/apoa5] A recent report, showed that, in the Sardinian population, the missense mutation **Arg282Ser** in the APOA5 gene correlates with a decrease in TG levels.
[src:lipid/apoa5] The authors believe that this point mutation is a major modulator of TG values in this population.
[src:lipid/apoa5] In humans, plasma triglycerides such as triacylglycerols have been long debated as an important risk factor for not only cardiovascular disease but also for other relevant morbidities, such as cancer, renal disease, suicide, and all-cause mortality.
[src:lipid/apoa5] The APOA5 gene was found by comparative sequencing of ~200 kbp of human and mice DNA as the last member of the gene cluster of apolipoproteins located on human chromosome 11 at 11q23.
[src:lipid/apoa5] Two mouse transgenic mouse models (APOA5 transgenic and APOA5 knockout) confirmed the important role of this gene in plasma triglyceride levels of plasma triglycerides.
[src:lipid/apoa5] Obesity and metabolic syndrome are both closely related to plasma triglyceride levels and APOA5.
[src:lipid/apoa5] Recent meta-analyses suggest that the effect on metabolic syndrome development is more profound for rs662799 in Asian population and for rs3135506 for Europeans.
[src:lipid/apoa5] Moreover, meta-analysis that focused on rs662799 and the risk of type 2 diabetes mellitus has suggested a significant association in Asian populations, but not in European populations.
[src:lipid/apoa5] Even though plasma concentration of APOA5 is very low, some studies have focused on the analysis of the potential association of this biochemical parameter with cardiovascular disease (CVD).
[src:lipid/apoa5] This relationship remains controversial, as higher plasma levels of APOA5 in individuals with CVD disease have been found in some, but not in all studies.
[src:lipid/apoa5] The major effect of the apolipoprotein A5 gene (and its variants) is on plasma triglyceride levels.
[src:lipid/apoa5] Minor alleles (C1131 and Trp19) are primarily associated with the elevation of plasma triglyceride levels.
[src:lipid/apoa5] The most extensive information available has been drawn from Caucasian populations, particularly in relation to the rs662799 SNP.
[src:lipid/apoa5] Here, one minor allele is associated with an approximate 0.25 mmol/L increase of plasma TG levels.
[src:lipid/apoa5] A similar effect is associated with the Trp19 allele, even though it has not been confirmed by a large number of studies.
[src:lipid/apoa5] Original studies have further described that the strongest effect of APOA5 polymorphisms on plasma TG levels is observed among Hispanics, with only minor effects detected among Africans.
[src:lipid/apoa5] Among Asians, the effect on plasma TG levels is similar to that found among Caucasians.
[src:lipid/apoa5] Generally, studies have suggested significant interethnic differences and in some cases sex-dependent associations as well.
[src:lipid/apoa5] Sporadic publications have also mentioned a weak but nonetheless significant effect of APOA5 variants on plasma HDL-cholesterol and non-HDL cholesterol levels.
[src:lipid/apoa5] A large meta-analysis of 101 studies confirmed a risk associated with the presence of the minor APOA5 allele -1131C and coronary heart disease.
[src:lipid/apoa5] The odds ratio was 1.18 for every C allele.
[src:lipid/apoa5] There are far fewer studies on the second common APOA5 polymorphism, Ser19>Trp, even though available studies have detected that its effect on plasma triglycerides is similar to C-1131>T.
[src:lipid/apoa5] Nevertheless, the minor Trp allele is also associated with increased risk of CVD, and it seems that especially homozygotes and carriers of more minor alleles (both -1131C and 19Trp) are at higher risk of CVD.
[src:lipid/apoa5] A multi-locus genetic risk score study based on a combination of 27 loci, including the APOA5 gene, identified individuals at increased risk for both incident and recurrent coronary artery disease events, as well as an enhanced clinical benefit from statin therapy.
[src:lipid/apoa5] The study was based on a community cohort study (the Malmo Diet and Cancer study) and four additional randomized controlled trials of primary prevention cohorts (JUPITER and ASCOT) and secondary prevention cohorts (CARE and PROVE IT-TIMI 22).
[src:lipid/apoa5] Obesity and metabolic syndrome are both closely related to plasma triglyceride levels.
[src:lipid/apoa5] Therefore, the focus on an association between APOA5 and BMI or metabolic syndrome is understandable.
[src:lipid/apoa5] Available studies show that minor APOA5 alleles could be associated with an enhanced risk of obesity or metabolic syndrome development.
[src:lipid/apoa5] However, genome wide studies have failed to prove that APOA5 is a gene associated with BMI values and/or obesity, so the effect could be far from clinically significant or at least significantly context-dependent.
[src:lipid/apoa5] Due to the high heterogeneity of the examined populations, differences in protocol and/or interventions used, the studies are difficult to directly compare and draw definitive conclusions.
[src:lipid/apoa5] However, with caution, it could be concluded that carriers of the minor C-1131, Trp19, or T553 alleles are in some cases less prone to the positive effects of environmental and/or pharmacological interventions.
[src:lipid/apoa5] Some papers suggest the importance of the interactions between APOA5 and other genes, especially with common APOE (OMIM acc.
[src:lipid/apoa5] 107741) three allelic (E2, E3, and E4) polymorphism, in the modulation of plasma lipids.
[src:lipid/apoa5] In these cases, the interaction between minor alleles of both genes seems to be of importance.
[src:lipid/apoa5] In the general population, APOE4 seems to have the potential to diminish the effect of minor APOA5 rs662799 and rs3135506 alleles, especially in females.
[src:lipid/apoa5] Interaction between APOE and APOA5 Ser19˃Trp has been suggested to play some role in the development of type III hyperlipidaemia.
[src:lipid/apoa5] Further studies, in which interaction with APOA5 has been described, have included, for example, variants within FTO, lipoprotein lipase, USF-1 and FEN-1.
[src:lipid/apoa5] They have also focused not only on plasma lipids, but on BMI values or hypertension as well.
[src:lipid/apoa5] Some other possible roles of APOA5 variants have been discussed, but generally these reports comprise only one or two papers – and first original papers with positive findings are usually not confirmed in second publications.
[src:lipid/apoa5] These papers focus on the possible effect of different APOA5 variants on maternal height, longer foetal birth length, putative associations with plasma levels of C-reactive protein, LDL particle size and haemostatic markers.
[src:lipid/apoa5] Despite the very low plasma concentration, variants within apolipoprotein A5 are potent determinants of plasma triglyceride levels.
[src:lipid/apoa5] Minor alleles of three SNPs (rs662799, rs3135506, rs3135507) are associated with the higher risk of cardiovascular disease.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] ATP synthase lies across a cellular membrane and forms an aperture that protons can cross from areas of high concentration to areas of low concentration, imparting energy for the synthesis of ATP.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] This electrochemical gradient is generated by the electron transport chain and allows cells to store energy in ATP for later use.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] In prokaryotic cells ATP synthase lies across the plasma membrane, while in eukaryotic cells it lies across the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] Organisms capable of photosynthesis also have ATP synthase across the thylakoid membrane, which in plants is located in the chloroplast and in cyanobacteria is located in the cytoplasm.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] ATP synthase is present in all organisms studied.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] Eukaryotic ATP synthases are F-ATPases (which usually work as ATP synthases instead of ATPases in cellular environments) and running "in reverse" for an ATPase (ATPases catalyze the decomposition of ATP into ADP and a free phosphate ion).
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] This article deals mainly with this type.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] An F-ATPase consists of two main subunits, FO and F1, which has a rotational motor mechanism allowing for ATP production.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] The F1 fraction derives its name from the term "Fraction 1" and FO (written as a subscript letter "o", not "zero") derives its name from being the binding fraction for oligomycin, a type of naturally derived antibiotic that is able to inhibit the FO unit of ATP synthase.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] These functional regions consist of different protein subunits — refer to tables.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] This enzyme is used in synthesis of ATP through aerobic respiration.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] Located within the thylakoid membrane and the inner mitochondrial membrane, ATP synthase consists of two regions FO and F1.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] FO causes rotation of F1 and is made of c-ring and subunits a, two b, F6.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] F1 has a water-soluble part that can hydrolyze ATP.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] FO on the other hand has mainly hydrophobic regions.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] FO F1 creates a pathway for protons movement across the membrane.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] The F1 portion of ATP synthase is hydrophilic and responsible for hydrolyzing ATP.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] The F1 unit protrudes into the cytoplasm (matrix and stroma in mitochondria and chloroplasts respectively).
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] Subunits α and β make a hexamer with 6 binding sites.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] Three of them are catalytically inactive and they bind ADP.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] Three other subunits catalyze the ATP synthesis.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] The other F1 subunits γ, δ, and ε are a part of a rotational motor mechanism (rotor/axle).
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] The γ subunit allows β to go through conformational changes (i.e., closed, half open, and open states) that allow for ATP to be bound and released once synthesized.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] The F1 particle is large and can be seen in the transmission electron microscope by negative staining.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] These are particles of 9 nm diameter that pepper the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] FO is a water insoluble protein with eight subunits and a transmembrane ring.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] The FO region of ATP synthase is a proton pore that is embedded in the mitochondrial membrane.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] It consists of three main subunits, a, b, and c.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] Six c subunits make up the rotor ring, and subunit b makes up a stalk connecting to F1 OSCP that prevents the αβ hexamer from rotating.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] Humans have six additional subunits, d, e, f, g, F6, and 8 (or A6L).
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] This part of the enzyme is located in the mitochondrial inner membrane and couples proton translocation to the rotation that causes ATP synthesis in the F1 region.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] In eukaryotes, mitochondrial FO forms membrane-bending dimers.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] These dimers self-arrange into long rows at the end of the cristae, possibly the first step of cristae formation.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] An atomic model for the dimeric yeast FO region was determined by cryo-EM at an overall resolution of 3.6 Å.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] In the 1960s through the 1970s, Paul Boyer, a UCLA Professor, developed the binding change, or flip-flop, mechanism theory, which postulated that ATP synthesis is dependent on a conformational change in ATP synthase generated by rotation of the gamma subunit.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] Walker, then at the MRC Laboratory of Molecular Biology in Cambridge, crystallized the F1 catalytic-domain of ATP synthase.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] The structure, at the time the largest asymmetric protein structure known, indicated that Boyer's rotary-catalysis model was, in essence, correct.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] For elucidating this, Boyer and Walker shared half of the 1997 Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] The crystal structure of the F1 showed alternating alpha and beta subunits (3 of each), arranged like segments of an orange around a rotating asymmetrical gamma subunit.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] A portion of the FO (the ring of c-subunits) rotates as the protons pass through the membrane.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] The c-ring is tightly attached to the asymmetric central stalk (consisting primarily of the gamma subunit), causing it to rotate within the alpha3beta3 of F1 causing the 3 catalytic nucleotide binding sites to go through a series of conformational changes that lead to ATP synthesis.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] The major F1 subunits are prevented from rotating in sympathy with the central stalk rotor by a peripheral stalk that joins the alpha3beta3 to the non-rotating portion of FO.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] The structure of the intact ATP synthase is currently known at low-resolution from electron cryo-microscopy (cryo-EM) studies of the complex.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] The cryo-EM model of ATP synthase suggests that the peripheral stalk is a flexible structure that wraps around the complex as it joins F1 to FO.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] Under the right conditions, the enzyme reaction can also be carried out in reverse, with ATP hydrolysis driving proton pumping across the membrane.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] The binding change mechanism involves the active site of a β subunit's cycling between three states.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] In the "loose" state, ADP and phosphate enter the active site; in the adjacent diagram, this is shown in pink.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] The enzyme then undergoes a change in shape and forces these molecules together, with the active site in the resulting "tight" state (shown in red) binding the newly produced ATP molecule with very high affinity.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] Finally, the active site cycles back to the open state (orange), releasing ATP and binding more ADP and phosphate, ready for the next cycle of ATP production.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] Like other enzymes, the activity of F1FO ATP synthase is reversible.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] Large-enough quantities of ATP cause it to create a transmembrane proton gradient, this is used by fermenting bacteria that do not have an electron transport chain, but rather hydrolyze ATP to make a proton gradient, which they use to drive flagella and the transport of nutrients into the cell.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] In respiring bacteria under physiological conditions, ATP synthase, in general, runs in the opposite direction, creating ATP while using the proton motive force created by the electron transport chain as a source of energy.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] The overall process of creating energy in this fashion is termed oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] The same process takes place in the mitochondria, where ATP synthase is located in the inner mitochondrial membrane and the F1-part projects into the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] By pumping proton cations into the matrix, the ATP-synthase converts ADP into ATP.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] The evolution of ATP synthase is thought to have been modular whereby two functionally independent subunits became associated and gained new functionality.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] This association appears to have occurred early in evolutionary history, because essentially the same structure and activity of ATP synthase enzymes are present in all kingdoms of life.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] The F-ATP synthase displays high functional and mechanistic similarity to the V-ATPase.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] However, whereas the F-ATP synthase generates ATP by utilising a proton gradient, the V-ATPase generates a proton gradient at the expense of ATP, generating pH values of as low as 1.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] The F1 region also shows significant similarity to hexameric DNA helicases (especially the Rho factor), and the entire enzyme region shows some similarity to H+ -powered T3SS or flagellar motor complexes.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] The α3β3 hexamer of the F1 region shows significant structural similarity to hexameric DNA helicases; both form a ring with 3-fold rotational symmetry with a central pore.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] The H+ motor of the FO particle shows great functional similarity to the H+ motors that drive flagella.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] Both feature a ring of many small alpha-helical proteins that rotate relative to nearby stationary proteins, using a H+ potential gradient as an energy source.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] This link is tenuous, however, as the overall structure of flagellar motors is far more complex than that of the FO particle and the ring with about 30 rotating proteins is far larger than the 10, 11, or 14 helical proteins in the FO complex.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] More recent structural data do however show that the ring and the stalk are structurally similar to the F1 particle.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] The modular evolution theory for the origin of ATP synthase suggests that two subunits with independent function, a DNA helicase with ATPase activity and a H+ motor, were able to bind, and the rotation of the motor drove the ATPase activity of the helicase in reverse.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] This complex then evolved greater efficiency and eventually developed into today's intricate ATP synthases.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] Alternatively, the DNA helicase/H+ motor complex may have had H+ pump activity with the ATPase activity of the helicase driving the H+ motor in reverse.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] This may have evolved to carry out the reverse reaction and act as an ATP synthase.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] A variety of natural and synthetic inhibitors of ATP synthase have been discovered.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] These have been used to probe the structure and mechanism of ATP synthase.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] There are several classes of ATP synthase inhibitors, including peptide inhibitors, polyphenolic phytochemicals, polyketides, organotin compounds, polyenic α-pyrone derivatives, cationic inhibitors, substrate analogs, amino acid modifiers, and other miscellaneous chemicals.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] Some of the most commonly used ATP synthase inhibitors are oligomycin and DCCD.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] Bacterial F-ATPases can occasionally operate in reverse, turning them into an ATPase.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] Some bacteria have no F-ATPase, using an A/V-type ATPase bidirectionally.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] Yeast ATP synthase is one of the best-studied eukaryotic ATP synthases; and five F1, eight FO subunits, and seven associated proteins have been identified.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] Most of these proteins have homologues in other eukaryotes.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] In plants, ATP synthase is also present in chloroplasts (CF1FO-ATP synthase).
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] The enzyme is integrated into thylakoid membrane; the CF1-part sticks into stroma, where dark reactions of photosynthesis (also called the light-independent reactions or the Calvin cycle) and ATP synthesis take place.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] The overall structure and the catalytic mechanism of the chloroplast ATP synthase are almost the same as those of the bacterial enzyme.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] However, in chloroplasts, the proton motive force is generated not by respiratory electron transport chain but by primary photosynthetic proteins.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] The synthase has a 40-aa insert in the gamma-subunit to inhibit wasteful activity when dark.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] The ATP synthase isolated from bovine (*Bos taurus*) heart mitochondria is, in terms of biochemistry and structure, the best-characterized ATP synthase.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] Beef heart is used as a source for the enzyme because of the high concentration of mitochondria in cardiac muscle.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] Their genes have close homology to human ATP synthases.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] Eukaryotes belonging to some divergent lineages have very special organizations of the ATP synthase.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] A euglenozoa ATP synthase forms a dimer with a boomerang-shaped F1 head like other mitochondrial ATP synthases, but the FO subcomplex has many unique subunits.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] The inhibitory IF1 also binds differently, in a way shared with trypanosomatida.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] Apicomplexans, such as *Plasmodium*, utilise a hexameric ATP synthase organisation existing as a trimer of ATP synthase dimers.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] These hexameric assemblies arrange into pentagonal pyramids, which induce a unique bulbous cristae membrane morphology.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] This organisation is underpinned by both apicomplexan-specific subunits and cardiolipins.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] Archaea do not generally have an F-ATPase.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] Instead, they synthesize ATP using the A-ATPase/synthase, a rotary machine structurally similar to the V-ATPase but mainly functioning as an ATP synthase.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] Like the bacteria F-ATPase, it is believed to also function as an ATPase.
[src:lipid/atp-synthase] F-ATPase gene linkage and gene order are widely conserved across ancient prokaryote lineages, implying that this system already existed at a date before the last universal common ancestor, the LUCA.
[src:lipid/lipid] Lipids are broadly defined as hydrophobic or amphiphilic small molecules; the amphiphilic nature of some lipids allows them to form structures such as vesicles, multilamellar/unilamellar liposomes, or membranes in an aqueous environment.
[src:lipid/lipid] Biological lipids originate entirely or in part from two distinct types of biochemical subunits or "building-blocks": ketoacyl and isoprene groups.
[src:lipid/lipid] Using this approach, lipids may be divided into eight categories: fatty acyls, glycerolipids, glycerophospholipids, sphingolipids, saccharolipids, and polyketides (derived from condensation of ketoacyl subunits); and sterol lipids and prenol lipids (derived from condensation of isoprene subunits).
[src:lipid/lipid] Although the term *lipid* is sometimes used as a synonym for fats, fats are a subgroup of lipids called triglycerides.
[src:lipid/lipid] Lipids also encompass molecules such as fatty acids and their derivatives (including tri-, di-, and monoglycerides, and phospholipids), as well as other sterol-containing metabolites such as cholesterol.
[src:lipid/lipid] Although humans and other mammals use various biosynthetic pathways both to break down and to synthesize lipids, some essential lipids cannot be made this way and must be obtained from the diet.
[src:lipid/lipid] In 1815, Henri Braconnot classified lipids (*graisses*) into two categories, *suifs* (solid greases or tallow) and *huiles* (fluid oils).
[src:lipid/lipid] In 1823, Michel Eugène Chevreul developed a more detailed classification, including oils, greases, tallow, waxes, resins, balsams and volatile oils (or essential oils).
[src:lipid/lipid] In 1827, William Prout recognized fat ("oily" alimentary matters), along with protein ("albuminous") and carbohydrate ("saccharine"), as an important nutrient for humans and animals.
[src:lipid/lipid] The first synthetic triglyceride was reported by Théophile-Jules Pelouze in 1844, when he produced tributyrin by treating butyric acid with glycerin in the presence of concentrated sulfuric acid.
[src:lipid/lipid] Several years later, Marcellin Berthelot, one of Pelouze's students, synthesized tristearin and tripalmitin by reaction of the analogous fatty acids with glycerin in the presence of gaseous hydrogen chloride at high temperature.
[src:lipid/lipid] For a century, chemists regarded "fats" as only simple lipids made of fatty acids and glycerol (glycerides), but new forms were described later.
[src:lipid/lipid] Theodore Gobley (1847) discovered phospholipids in mammalian brain and hen egg, called by him as "lecithins".
[src:lipid/lipid] Thudichum discovered in the human brain some phospholipids (cephalin), glycolipids (cerebroside) and sphingolipids (sphingomyelin).
[src:lipid/lipid] The terms lipoid, lipin, lipide and lipid have been used with varied meanings from author to author.
[src:lipid/lipid] In 1912, Rosenbloom and Gies proposed the substitution of "lipoid" by "lipin".
[src:lipid/lipid] In 1920, Bloor introduced a new classification for "lipoids": simple lipoids (greases and waxes), compound lipoids (phospholipoids and glycolipoids), and the derived lipoids (fatty acids, alcohols, sterols).
[src:lipid/lipid] The word *lipide*, which stems etymologically from Greek λίπος, *lipos* 'fat', was introduced in 1923 by the French pharmacologist Gabriel Bertrand.
[src:lipid/lipid] Bertrand included in the concept not only the traditional fats (glycerides), but also the "lipoids", with a complex constitution.
[src:lipid/lipid] The word *lipide* was unanimously approved by the international commission of the *Société de Chimie Biologique* during the plenary session on July 3, 1923.
[src:lipid/lipid] The word *lipide* was later anglicized as *lipid* because of its pronunciation ('lɪpɪd).
[src:lipid/lipid] In French, the suffix *-ide*, from Ancient Greek -ίδης (meaning 'son of' or 'descendant of'), is always pronounced (ɪd).
[src:lipid/lipid] Hilditch defined "simple lipids" as greases and waxes (true waxes, sterols, alcohols).
[src:lipid/lipid] Fatty acyls, a generic term for describing fatty acids, their conjugates and derivatives, are a diverse group of molecules synthesized by chain-elongation of an acetyl-CoA primer with malonyl-CoA or methylmalonyl-CoA groups in a process called fatty acid synthesis.
[src:lipid/lipid] They are made of a hydrocarbon chain that terminates with a carboxylic acid group; this arrangement confers the molecule with a polar, hydrophilic end, and a nonpolar, hydrophobic end that is insoluble in water.
[src:lipid/lipid] The fatty acid structure is one of the most fundamental categories of biological lipids and is commonly used as a building-block of more structurally complex lipids.
[src:lipid/lipid] The carbon chain, typically between four and 24 carbons long, may be saturated or unsaturated, and may be attached to functional groups containing oxygen, halogens, nitrogen, and sulfur.
[src:lipid/lipid] If a fatty acid contains a double bond, there is the possibility of either a *cis* or *trans* geometric isomerism, which significantly affects the molecule's configuration.
[src:lipid/lipid] *Cis*-double bonds cause the fatty acid chain to bend, an effect that is compounded with more double bonds in the chain.
[src:lipid/lipid] This in turn plays an important role in the structure and function of cell membranes.
[src:lipid/lipid] Most naturally occurring fatty acids are of the *cis* configuration, although the *trans* form does exist in some natural and partially hydrogenated fats and oils.
[src:lipid/lipid] Examples of biologically important fatty acids include the eicosanoids, derived primarily from arachidonic acid and eicosapentaenoic acid, that include prostaglandins, leukotrienes, and thromboxanes.
[src:lipid/lipid] Docosahexaenoic acid is also important in biological systems, particularly with respect to sight.
[src:lipid/lipid] Other major lipid classes in the fatty acid category are the fatty esters and fatty amides.
[src:lipid/lipid] Fatty esters include important biochemical intermediates such as wax esters, fatty acid thioester coenzyme A derivatives, fatty acid thioester ACP derivatives and fatty acid carnitines.
[src:lipid/lipid] The fatty amides include N-acyl ethanolamines, such as the cannabinoid neurotransmitter anandamide.
[src:lipid/lipid] Glycerolipids are composed of mono-, di-, and tri-substituted glycerols, the best-known being the fatty acid triesters of glycerol, called triglycerides.
[src:lipid/lipid] The word "triacylglycerol" is sometimes used synonymously with "triglyceride".
[src:lipid/lipid] In these compounds, the three hydroxyl groups of glycerol are each esterified, typically by different fatty acids.
[src:lipid/lipid] Because they function as an energy store, these lipids comprise the bulk of storage fat in animal tissues.
[src:lipid/lipid] The hydrolysis of the ester bonds of triglycerides and the release of glycerol and fatty acids from adipose tissue are the initial steps in metabolizing fat.
[src:lipid/lipid] Additional subclasses of glycerolipids are represented by glycosylglycerols, which are characterized by the presence of one or more sugar residues attached to glycerol via a glycosidic linkage.
[src:lipid/lipid] Examples of structures in this category are the digalactosyldiacylglycerols found in plant membranes and seminolipid from mammalian sperm cells.
[src:lipid/lipid] Glycerophospholipids, usually referred to as phospholipids (though sphingomyelins are also classified as phospholipids), are ubiquitous in nature and are key components of the lipid bilayer of cells, as well as being involved in metabolism and cell signaling.
[src:lipid/lipid] Neural tissue (including the brain) contains relatively high amounts of glycerophospholipids, and alterations in their composition has been implicated in various neurological disorders.
[src:lipid/lipid] Glycerophospholipids may be subdivided into distinct classes, based on the nature of the polar headgroup at the *sn*-3 position of the glycerol backbone in eukaryotes and eubacteria, or the *sn*-1 position in the case of archaebacteria.
[src:lipid/lipid] Examples of glycerophospholipids found in biological membranes are phosphatidylcholine (also known as PC, GPCho or lecithin), phosphatidylethanolamine (PE or GPEtn) and phosphatidylserine (PS or GPSer).
[src:lipid/lipid] Typically, one or both of these hydroxyl groups are acylated with long-chain fatty acids, but there are also alkyl-linked and 1Z-alkenyl-linked (plasmalogen) glycerophospholipids, as well as dialkylether variants in archaebacteria.
[src:lipid/lipid] Sphingolipids are a complicated family of compounds that share a common structural feature, a sphingoid base backbone that is synthesized *de novo* from the amino acid serine and a long-chain fatty acyl CoA, then converted into ceramides, phosphosphingolipids, glycosphingolipids and other compounds.
[src:lipid/lipid] The major sphingoid base of mammals is commonly referred to as sphingosine.
[src:lipid/lipid] Ceramides (N-acyl-sphingoid bases) are a major subclass of sphingoid base derivatives with an amide-linked fatty acid.
[src:lipid/lipid] The fatty acids are typically saturated or mono-unsaturated with chain lengths from 16 to 26 carbon atoms.
[src:lipid/lipid] The major phosphosphingolipids of mammals are sphingomyelins (ceramide phosphocholines), whereas insects contain mainly ceramide phosphoethanolamines and fungi have phytoceramide phosphoinositols and mannose-containing headgroups.
[src:lipid/lipid] The glycosphingolipids are a diverse family of molecules composed of one or more sugar residues linked via a glycosidic bond to the sphingoid base.
[src:lipid/lipid] Examples of these are the simple and complex glycosphingolipids such as cerebrosides and gangliosides.
[src:lipid/lipid] Sterols, such as cholesterol and its derivatives, are an important component of membrane lipids, along with the glycerophospholipids and sphingomyelins.
[src:lipid/lipid] Other examples of sterols are the bile acids and their conjugates, which in mammals are oxidized derivatives of cholesterol and are synthesized in the liver.
[src:lipid/lipid] The plant equivalents are the phytosterols, such as β-sitosterol, stigmasterol, and brassicasterol; the latter compound is also used as a biomarker for algal growth.
[src:lipid/lipid] The predominant sterol in fungal cell membranes is ergosterol.
[src:lipid/lipid] Sterols are steroids in which one of the hydrogen atoms is substituted with a hydroxyl group, at position 3 in the carbon chain.
[src:lipid/lipid] They have in common with steroids the same fused four-ring core structure.
[src:lipid/lipid] Steroids have different biological roles as hormones and signaling molecules.
[src:lipid/lipid] The eighteen-carbon (C18) steroids include the estrogen family whereas the C19 steroids comprise the androgens such as testosterone and androsterone.
[src:lipid/lipid] The C21 subclass includes the progestogens as well as the glucocorticoids and mineralocorticoids.
[src:lipid/lipid] The secosteroids, comprising various forms of vitamin D, are characterized by cleavage of the B ring of the core structure.
[src:lipid/lipid] Prenol lipids are synthesized from the five-carbon-unit precursors isopentenyl diphosphate and dimethylallyl diphosphate, which are produced mainly via the mevalonic acid (MVA) pathway.
[src:lipid/lipid] The simple isoprenoids (linear alcohols, diphosphates, etc.) are formed by the successive addition of C5 units, and are classified according to number of these terpene units.
[src:lipid/lipid] Structures containing greater than 40 carbons are known as polyterpenes.
[src:lipid/lipid] Carotenoids are important simple isoprenoids that function as antioxidants and as precursors of vitamin A.
[src:lipid/lipid] Another biologically important class of molecules is exemplified by the quinones and hydroquinones, which contain an isoprenoid tail attached to a quinonoid core of non-isoprenoid origin.
[src:lipid/lipid] Vitamin E and vitamin K, as well as the ubiquinones, are examples of this class.
[src:lipid/lipid] Prokaryotes synthesize polyprenols (called bactoprenols) in which the terminal isoprenoid unit attached to oxygen remains unsaturated, whereas in animal polyprenols (dolichols) the terminal isoprenoid is reduced.
[src:lipid/lipid] Saccharolipids describe compounds in which fatty acids are linked to a sugar backbone, forming structures that are compatible with membrane bilayers.
[src:lipid/lipid] In the saccharolipids, a monosaccharide substitutes for the glycerol backbone present in glycerolipids and glycerophospholipids.
[src:lipid/lipid] The most familiar saccharolipids are the acylated glucosamine precursors of the Lipid A component of the lipopolysaccharides in Gram-negative bacteria.
[src:lipid/lipid] Typical lipid A molecules are disaccharides of glucosamine, which are derivatized with as many as seven fatty-acyl chains.
[src:lipid/lipid] The minimal lipopolysaccharide required for growth in *E. coli* is Kdo2-Lipid A, a hexa-acylated disaccharide of glucosamine that is glycosylated with two 3-deoxy-D-manno-octulosonic acid (Kdo) residues.
[src:lipid/lipid] Polyketides are synthesized by polymerization of acetyl and propionyl subunits by classic enzymes as well as iterative and multimodular enzymes that share mechanistic features with the fatty acid synthases.
[src:lipid/lipid] They comprise many secondary metabolites and natural products from animal, plant, bacterial, fungal and marine sources, and have great structural diversity.
[src:lipid/lipid] Many polyketides are cyclic molecules whose backbones are often further modified by glycosylation, methylation, hydroxylation, oxidation, or other processes.
[src:lipid/lipid] Many commonly used antimicrobial, antiparasitic, and anticancer agents are polyketides or polyketide derivatives, such as erythromycins, tetracyclines, avermectins, and antitumor epothilones.
[src:lipid/lipid] Eukaryotic cells feature the compartmentalized membrane-bound organelles that carry out different biological functions.
[src:lipid/lipid] The glycerophospholipids are the main structural component of biological membranes, as the cellular plasma membrane and the intracellular membranes of organelles; in animal cells, the plasma membrane physically separates the intracellular components from the extracellular environment.
[src:lipid/lipid] The glycerophospholipids are amphipathic molecules (containing both hydrophobic and hydrophilic regions) that contain a glycerol core linked to two fatty acid-derived "tails" by ester linkages and to one "head" group by a phosphate ester linkage.
[src:lipid/lipid] While glycerophospholipids are the major component of biological membranes, other non-glyceride lipid components such as sphingomyelin and sterols (mainly cholesterol in animal cell membranes) are also found in biological membranes.
[src:lipid/lipid] A biological membrane is a form of lamellar phase lipid bilayer.
[src:lipid/lipid] The formation of lipid bilayers is an energetically preferred process when the glycerophospholipids described above are in an aqueous environment.
[src:lipid/lipid] This is known as the hydrophobic effect.
[src:lipid/lipid] Other aggregations are also observed and form part of the polymorphism of amphiphile (lipid) behavior.
[src:lipid/lipid] Phase behavior is an area of study within biophysics.
[src:lipid/lipid] Micelles and bilayers form in the polar medium by a process known as the hydrophobic effect.
[src:lipid/lipid] When dissolving a lipophilic or amphiphilic substance in a polar environment, the polar molecules (i.e., water in an aqueous solution) become more ordered around the dissolved lipophilic substance, since the polar molecules cannot form hydrogen bonds to the lipophilic areas of the amphiphile.
[src:lipid/lipid] So in an aqueous environment, the water molecules form an ordered "clathrate" cage around the dissolved lipophilic molecule.
[src:lipid/lipid] The formation of lipids into protocell membranes represents a key step in models of abiogenesis, the origin of life.
[src:lipid/lipid] Triglycerides, stored in adipose tissue, are a major form of energy storage both in animals and plants.
[src:lipid/lipid] They are a major source of energy in aerobic respiration.
[src:lipid/lipid] The complete oxidation of fatty acids releases about 38 kJ/g (9 kcal/g), compared with only 17 kJ/g (4 kcal/g) for the oxidative breakdown of carbohydrates and proteins.
[src:lipid/lipid] The adipocyte, or fat cell, is designed for continuous synthesis and breakdown of triglycerides in animals, with breakdown controlled mainly by the activation of hormone-sensitive enzyme lipase.
[src:lipid/lipid] Migratory birds that must fly long distances without eating use triglycerides to fuel their flights.
[src:lipid/lipid] Evidence has emerged showing that lipid signaling is a vital part of the cell signaling.
[src:lipid/lipid] Lipid signaling may occur via activation of G protein-coupled or nuclear receptors, and members of several different lipid categories have been identified as signaling molecules and cellular messengers.
[src:lipid/lipid] Phosphatidylserine lipids are known to be involved in signaling for the phagocytosis of apoptotic cells or pieces of cells.
[src:lipid/lipid] They accomplish this by being exposed to the extracellular face of the cell membrane after the inactivation of flippases which place them exclusively on the cytosolic side and the activation of scramblases, which scramble the orientation of the phospholipids.
[src:lipid/lipid] After this occurs, other cells recognize the phosphatidylserines and phagocytosize the cells or cell fragments exposing them.
[src:lipid/lipid] The "fat-soluble" vitamins (A, D, E and K) – which are isoprene-based lipids – are essential nutrients stored in the liver and fatty tissues, with a diverse range of functions.
[src:lipid/lipid] Acyl-carnitines are involved in the transport and metabolism of fatty acids in and out of mitochondria, where they undergo beta oxidation.
[src:lipid/lipid] Polyprenols and their phosphorylated derivatives also play important transport roles, in this case the transport of oligosaccharides across membranes.
[src:lipid/lipid] Polyprenol phosphate sugars and polyprenol diphosphate sugars function in extra-cytoplasmic glycosylation reactions, in extracellular polysaccharide biosynthesis (for instance, peptidoglycan polymerization in bacteria), and in eukaryotic protein N-glycosylation.
[src:lipid/lipid] Cardiolipins are a subclass of glycerophospholipids containing four acyl chains and three glycerol groups that are particularly abundant in the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:lipid/lipid] They are believed to activate enzymes involved with oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:lipid/lipid] Lipids also form the basis of steroid hormones.
[src:lipid/lipid] The major dietary lipids for humans and other animals are animal and plant triglycerides, sterols, and membrane phospholipids.
[src:lipid/lipid] The process of lipid metabolism synthesizes and degrades the lipid stores and produces the structural and functional lipids characteristic of individual tissues.
[src:lipid/lipid] In animals, when there is an oversupply of dietary carbohydrate, the excess carbohydrate is converted to triglycerides.
[src:lipid/lipid] This involves the synthesis of fatty acids from acetyl-CoA and the esterification of fatty acids in the production of triglycerides, a process called lipogenesis.
[src:lipid/lipid] Fatty acids are made by fatty acid synthases that polymerize and then reduce acetyl-CoA units.
[src:lipid/lipid] The acyl chains in the fatty acids are extended by a cycle of reactions that add the acetyl group, reduce it to an alcohol, dehydrate it to an alkene group and then reduce it again to an alkane group.
[src:lipid/lipid] The enzymes of fatty acid biosynthesis are divided into two groups, in animals and fungi all these fatty acid synthase reactions are carried out by a single multifunctional protein, while in plant plastids and bacteria separate enzymes perform each step in the pathway.
[src:lipid/lipid] The fatty acids may be subsequently converted to triglycerides that are packaged in lipoproteins and secreted from the liver.
[src:lipid/lipid] The synthesis of unsaturated fatty acids involves a desaturation reaction, whereby a double bond is introduced into the fatty acyl chain.
[src:lipid/lipid] For example, in humans, the desaturation of stearic acid by stearoyl-CoA desaturase-1 produces oleic acid.
[src:lipid/lipid] The doubly unsaturated fatty acid linoleic acid as well as the triply unsaturated α-linolenic acid cannot be synthesized in mammalian tissues, and are therefore essential fatty acids and must be obtained from the diet.
[src:lipid/lipid] Triglyceride synthesis takes place in the endoplasmic reticulum by metabolic pathways in which acyl groups in fatty acyl-CoAs are transferred to the hydroxyl groups of glycerol-3-phosphate and diacylglycerol.
[src:lipid/lipid] Terpenes and isoprenoids, including the carotenoids, are made by the assembly and modification of isoprene units donated from the reactive precursors isopentenyl pyrophosphate and dimethylallyl pyrophosphate.
[src:lipid/lipid] These precursors can be made in different ways.
[src:lipid/lipid] In animals and archaea, the mevalonate pathway produces these compounds from acetyl-CoA, while in plants and bacteria the non-mevalonate pathway uses pyruvate and glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate as substrates.
[src:lipid/lipid] One important reaction that uses these activated isoprene donors is steroid biosynthesis.
[src:lipid/lipid] Here, the isoprene units are joined together to make squalene and then folded up and formed into a set of rings to make lanosterol.
[src:lipid/lipid] Lanosterol can then be converted into other steroids such as cholesterol and ergosterol.
[src:lipid/lipid] Beta oxidation is the metabolic process by which fatty acids are broken down in the mitochondria or in peroxisomes to generate acetyl-CoA.
[src:lipid/lipid] For the most part, fatty acids are oxidized by a mechanism that is similar to, but not identical with, a reversal of the process of fatty acid synthesis.
[src:lipid/lipid] That is, two-carbon fragments are removed sequentially from the carboxyl end of the acid after steps of dehydrogenation, hydration, and oxidation to form a beta-keto acid, which is split by thiolysis.
[src:lipid/lipid] The acetyl-CoA is then ultimately converted into adenosine triphosphate (ATP), CO2, and H2O using the citric acid cycle and the electron transport chain.
[src:lipid/lipid] Hence the citric acid cycle can start at acetyl-CoA when fat is being broken down for energy if there is little or no glucose available.
[src:lipid/lipid] The energy yield of the complete oxidation of the fatty acid palmitate is 106 ATP.
[src:lipid/lipid] Unsaturated and odd-chain fatty acids require additional enzymatic steps for degradation.
[src:lipid/lipid] Most of the fat found in food is in the form of triglycerides, cholesterol, and phospholipids.
[src:lipid/lipid] Some dietary fat is necessary to facilitate absorption of fat-soluble vitamins (A, D, E, and K) and carotenoids.
[src:lipid/lipid] Humans and other mammals have a dietary requirement for certain essential fatty acids, such as linoleic acid (an omega-6 fatty acid) and alpha-linolenic acid (an omega-3 fatty acid) because they cannot be synthesized from simple precursors in the diet.
[src:lipid/lipid] Both of these fatty acids are 18-carbon polyunsaturated fatty acids differing in the number and position of the double bonds.
[src:lipid/lipid] Most vegetable oils are rich in linoleic acid (safflower, sunflower, and corn oils).
[src:lipid/lipid] Alpha-linolenic acid is found in the green leaves of plants and in some seeds, nuts, and legumes (in particular flax, rapeseed, walnut, and soy).
[src:lipid/lipid] Fish oils are particularly rich in the longer-chain omega-3 fatty acids eicosapentaenoic acid and docosahexaenoic acid.
[src:lipid/lipid] Many studies have shown positive health benefits associated with consumption of omega-3 fatty acids on infant development, cancer, cardiovascular diseases, and various mental illnesses (such as depression, attention-deficit hyperactivity disorder, and dementia).
[src:lipid/lipid] In contrast, it is now well-established that consumption of trans fats, such as those present in partially hydrogenated vegetable oils, are a risk factor for cardiovascular disease.
[src:lipid/lipid] Fats that are good for one may be turned into trans fats by improper cooking methods that result in overcooking the lipids.
[src:lipid/lipid] Results from recent clinical trials have linked long-term variation in lipids, including LDL and triglycerides, with risk of cardiovascular disease, diabetes, or heart failure.
[src:lipid/lipid] Excessive lipid variability has been linked to oxidative stress and endothelial dysfunction.
[src:lipid/lipid] A few studies have suggested that total dietary fat intake is linked to an increased risk of obesity and diabetes.
[src:lipid/lipid] Others, including the Women's Health Initiative Dietary Modification Trial, an eight-year study of 49,000 women, the Nurses' Health Study, and the Health Professionals Follow-up Study, revealed no such links.
[src:lipid/lipid] None of these studies suggested any connection between percentage of calories from fat and risk of cancer, heart disease, or weight gain.
[src:lipid/lipid] The Nutrition Source, a website maintained by the department of nutrition at the T.
